The relative distribution of the 3 types of treatments did not vary significantly during the study period (A2). However, within the rate-control group, use of beta blockers increased significantly from 40% in 1999 to 68% in 2008, with an estimated annual increase of 2.8% over the study period (P < .001; Figure 1
). This is accompanied by a significant decrease in the use of digoxin as the initial treatment with an annual decrease of 3.5% a year (Figure 1). For initial nonpharmacotherapy, cardioversion was the most common procedure which was performed in about 85% of the patients in this group; RFCAs accounted for the remaining 15% of the patients. The Maze procedure was only observed since 2006 and increased gradually to about 5% of patients receiving nonpharmacotherapy as the initial treatment in 2008 (A3
). The relative distribution of these procedures remained steady over time.
